Gulfport ( /ɡʌlfˌpɔːrt/ GUHLF-port ) is a prominent [port city](/Port_city) nestled within [Harrison County, Mississippi](/Harrison_County,_Mississippi), proudly serving as one of its two co-[county seats](/County_seat). As of the [2020 United States census](/2020_United_States_census), this coastal hub boasted a population of 72,926 residents, solidifying its position as the [second-most populous city in Mississippi](/List_of_municipalities_in_Mississippi), just trailing behind the state's capital, [Jackson](/Jackson,_Mississippi) [5]. The broader [Gulfport–Biloxi metropolitan area](/Gulfport%E2%80%93Biloxi_metropolitan_area), a sprawling urban expanse, housed a considerable population of 416,259 individuals, further emphasizing the region's significance [6]. Situated strategically along the sun-drenched [Gulf Coast of the United States](/Gulf_Coast_of_the_United_States) in southern Mississippi, Gulfport aptly derives its name from its direct access to the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) via its bustling port on the tranquil [Mississippi Sound](/Mississippi_Sound).

The modern incarnation of Gulfport didn't simply appear; it coalesced from two antecedent settlements: the coastal [Mississippi City](/Mississippi_City,_Mississippi) and the bayou-adjacent Handsboro. Its formal genesis can be traced to 1887, when [William H. Hardy](/William_H._Hardy) envisioned it as the vital terminus for the ambitious [Gulf and Ship Island Railroad](/Gulf_and_Ship_Island_Railroad). However, the city's true trajectory of development was largely shaped by the financial might and foresight of [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia) [oil tycoon](/Business_magnate) [Joseph T. Jones](/Joseph_T._Jones). Jones, with a commitment that bordered on the obsessive, not only bankrolled the railroad but also funded the very infrastructure of the city itself, including the creation of its harbor and the arduous dredging of its essential shipping channel. The city officially achieved its [municipal incorporation](/Municipal_incorporation) on July 28, 1898, marking the formal beginning of its journey. By the dawn of the 20th century, Gulfport had briefly, yet spectacularly, risen to become the largest lumber export city in the [United States](/United_States), a status it held until the inevitable depletion of Mississippi's vast [Piney Woods](/Piney_Woods) timber resources. Following this natural resource shift, the city shrewdly pivoted its economic focus, transitioning into a vibrant center for tourism, capitalizing on its pristine white beaches, the allure of its [grand hotels](/Historic_Grand_Hotels_on_the_Mississippi_Gulf_Coast), and the significant revenue generated by its burgeoning [casino](/Casino) gaming operations.

Today, the bedrock of Gulfport's economy is multifaceted, primarily anchored by substantial military operations, a robust tourism sector, comprehensive healthcare services, and its enduring role in maritime commerce. The city proudly hosts the [Naval Construction Battalion Center](/Naval_Construction_Battalion_Center_(Gulfport,_Mississippi)), a critical military installation, alongside the [Gulfport Combat Readiness Training Center](/Gulfport_Combat_Readiness_Training_Center), and serves as home to a campus of [Mississippi Gulf Coast Community College](/Mississippi_Gulf_Coast_Community_College). The [Port of Gulfport](/Port_of_Gulfport) remains one of the busiest and most vital ports in the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico), facilitating extensive trade, while the [Gulfport-Biloxi International Airport](/Gulfport%E2%80%93Biloxi_International_Airport) ensures commercial air connectivity for the entire region. Despite enduring the devastating wrath of two of the most powerful hurricanes in recorded history—[Hurricane Camille](/Hurricane_Camille) in 1969 and [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina) in 2005—the city has demonstrated an almost defiant resilience, consistently rebuilding, modernizing, and expanding its infrastructure and facilities, a testament to its tenacious spirit [7].

### History

Before Gulfport even registered as a glimmer in a land speculator's eye, this stretch of the [Mississippi](/Mississippi) coast was already inhabited by two distinct, older settlements: [Mississippi City](/Mississippi_City,_Mississippi), strategically positioned along the gulf's edge, and Handsboro, which had taken root in the 1800s further inland, nestled amongst the meandering northern bayous [8] [9]. [Mississippi City](/Mississippi_City,_Mississippi) itself was the brainchild of the Mississippi City Company, formed in 1837 with the ambitious goal of constructing a town destined to be the grand terminus for the proposed [Gulf and Ship Island Railroad](/Gulf_and_Ship_Island_Railroad) [10] [11]. The primary, rather straightforward, purpose of this railroad was to efficiently transport valuable [yellow pine](/Yellow_pine) timber from the interior for lucrative ship-based trade [12]. However, the dreams of a bustling rail hub were abruptly derailed by an economic depression, leading to the abandonment of the railroad project. Nevertheless, the town itself persevered and, upon the official creation of [Harrison County](/Harrison_County,_Mississippi) in 1841, was rather unceremoniously designated as the [county seat](/County_seat) [8] [13].

Years later, the [Gulf and Ship Island Railroad](/Gulf_and_Ship_Island_Railroad) company, proving that some ideas simply refuse to die, underwent a reorganization, appointing [William H. Hardy](/William_H._Hardy) as its new president. Hardy, a man with a vision—and presumably, a strong sense of self-preservation—aimed to connect the railroad from the town of [Hattiesburg](/Hattiesburg,_Mississippi), which he himself had founded, directly to the coast. He deliberately bypassed [Mississippi City](/Mississippi_City,_Mississippi), a decision based on its rather inconvenient lack of proximity to genuinely deep water [13]. Instead, he selected the site that would become Gulfport in 1887, marking the town's initial, somewhat precarious, founding [14]. The sheer scale and financial demands of the project, however, proved too much even for Hardy, leading to his bankruptcy in 1893 and consequently transforming the nascent town into something akin to a [ghost town](/Ghost_town) [13]. Yet, as fate, or rather, capital, would have it, [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia) [oil tycoon](/Business_magnate) [Joseph T. Jones](/Joseph_T._Jones) stepped in, acquiring the company and injecting it with the necessary lifeblood [13] [14]. Jones, a figure whose ambition clearly dwarfed mere inconvenience, not only financed the completion of the railroad but also provided the substantial funds required to develop much of the city's infrastructure, including the critical harbor and the continuous, exhaustive dredging of the shipping channel [14]. In a moment of rather pedestrian origin, the city was given its definitive name in 1888 by R. H. Henry, editor of the [Jackson Clarion-Ledger](/The_Clarion-Ledger), after a conversation with Hardy [14]. Finally, on July 28, 1898, the city was officially incorporated, securing its place on the map. A few years later, in 1902, [Harrison County](/Harrison_County,_Mississippi) residents, perhaps weary of their previous arrangement, voted to relocate the [county seat](/County_seat) to the burgeoning Gulfport [8].

**Steamer loading resin in Gulfport, 1906**

The turn of the 20th century saw the fruits of Jones's investment, with the railroad finally completed in 1900 and the [Port of Gulfport](/Port_of_Gulfport) achieving full operational status by 1902 [13]. On April 28, 1904, the [Treasury Department](/United_States_Department_of_the_Treasury), in a move that likely ruffled some feathers further west, officially shifted the [port of entry](/Port_of_entry) for the district of the Pearl River from [Shieldsboro](/Bay_St._Louis,_Mississippi) to Gulfport [15]. This decision was largely driven by Gulfport's superior ease of access compared to its more established rivals, [Mobile](/Mobile,_Alabama) or [New Orleans](/New_Orleans) [13]. The port quickly propelled Gulfport to an almost unbelievable prominence, making it the largest lumber export city in the [United States](/United_States), a title it cemented by shipping over 293 million feet of lumber in 1906. This golden era, however, proved fleeting, as the relentless depletion of the region's [yellow pine](/Yellow_pine) forests brought this status to an abrupt end in the early 20th century [13].

Despite the timber industry's eventual decline, the city itself experienced remarkable growth. By 1900, the population had swelled to a modest 1,000, but by 1910, it had surged past 6,000 residents, a clear indicator of its burgeoning appeal [13]. This rapid expansion necessitated the establishment of essential municipal services; a fire department was formed, sanitation services were put in place, and by 1903, a proper county courthouse stood as a symbol of civic order [12] [13]. The [Louisville and Nashville](/Louisville_and_Nashville_Railroad) railroad line also began servicing the city around this period, connecting it to the wider national network at [Gulfport Station](/Gulfport_station) (then known, rather grandiosely, as the [Union Depot](/Union_station)) [13]. Further cementing its modernity, the [U.S. Post Office and Customhouse](/United_States_Post_Office_and_Customhouse_(Gulfport,_Mississippi)) was constructed in 1910 [16], and in March 1916, the mayor proudly announced the impending construction of a [Carnegie Library](/Carnegie_Library), a beacon of knowledge and, let's be honest, civic pride [17]. Other notable advancements of this era included the construction of the opulent [Great Southern Hotel](/Historic_Grand_Hotels_on_the_Mississippi_Gulf_Coast), the establishment of an electric plant (which would later fall under the capable, or perhaps simply omnipresent, management of [Mississippi Power](/Mississippi_Power)), and the introduction of a convenient [streetcar](/Tram) line, ferrying residents around their increasingly sophisticated city [13].

In 1917, Gulfport was poised to host the grand Mississippi Centennial Exposition, an event designed to showcase the state's progress and potential. However, the [United States](/United_States)'s entry into [World War I](/World_War_I) abruptly scuttled these ambitious plans. The impressive complex of buildings erected for the exposition was repurposed, rather than wasted, and transferred to the [U.S. Navy](/United_States_Navy) to serve as a vital training center, a stark shift from celebratory to strategic. These lands would eventually transition once more, becoming the site of a [Veterans Administration Hospital](/Gulfport_Veterans_Administration_Medical_Center_Historic_District), which dutifully served the community until 2005 [13] [18]. The 1920s, a decade often romanticized, brought a significant construction boom to Gulfport, with notable structures like the elegant [Hotel Markham](/Historic_Grand_Hotels_on_the_Mississippi_Gulf_Coast) and the solid Bank of Gulfport being completed, reflecting an era of prosperity and confidence [13]. By the 1930s, the city's population had continued its upward trajectory, surpassing 12,000, a trend of consistent expansion that extended well into the 1940s [13].

The tumultuous period of [World War II](/World_War_II) saw Gulfport transform into a strategic military hub, with the establishment of two significant bases. Camp Hollyday, founded in 1942, would eventually evolve into the permanent home base for the crucial [Naval Construction Battalion Center](/Naval_Construction_Battalion_Center_(Gulfport,_Mississippi)) [13]. Simultaneously, also in 1942, the [U.S. Army Air Corps](/United_States_Army_Air_Corps) constructed a dedicated training base for heavy bomber crews, which became known as [Gulfport Army Airfield](/Gulfport_Army_Airfield) [19]. Following the war's conclusion, the base was deemed surplus, and the city astutely acquired the majority of its facilities, converting them into the new [Gulfport Municipal Airport](/Gulfport%E2%80%93Biloxi_International_Airport) (it's worth noting that the city's *first* airport had been dedicated in 1930, demonstrating a consistent, if evolving, commitment to air travel) [19] [20]. In 1954, the [U.S. Air Force](/United_States_Air_Force) temporarily resumed its presence, utilizing the facilities they still owned as Gulfport Air Force Base for the training of [Air National Guard](/Air_National_Guard) units [20]. This arrangement was relatively short-lived, lasting until 1958 [21], at which point the facilities were permanently transferred to the [Mississippi Air National Guard](/Mississippi_Air_National_Guard), becoming the [Gulfport Combat Readiness Training Center](/Gulfport_Combat_Readiness_Training_Center) [19].

**U.S. President [Gerald Ford](/Gerald_Ford) visited Gulfport during his [1976 reelection campaign](/1976_United_States_presidential_election)**

By the mid-20th century, Gulfport's population continued its steady ascent, reaching approximately 22,000 by 1950 and expanding further to 30,000 residents by 1960 [13]. Echoing the broader civil rights struggles of the era, Gulfport experienced its own localized protest in 1960, a "wade-in" demonstration that mirrored the more widely known [Biloxi wade-ins](/Biloxi_wade-ins) [22]. In 1965, the city strategically expanded its boundaries, annexing the historically significant areas of [Mississippi City](/Mississippi_City,_Mississippi) and Handsboro, integrating these foundational communities into the larger municipal fabric [12]. However, this period of growth was dramatically interrupted on August 17, 1969, when Gulfport and the entire [Mississippi Gulf Coast](/Mississippi_Gulf_Coast) bore the brunt of [Hurricane Camille](/Hurricane_Camille), a meteorological behemoth that stands as the second-strongest hurricane to ever make landfall in the [United States](/United_States) in recorded history [23]. The devastation was particularly acute along the waterfront: storm waters in Gulfport surged to an astonishing 21 feet, effectively obliterating the [Port of Gulfport](/Port_of_Gulfport). Fortunately, the downtown and inland areas, while not entirely spared, sustained comparatively minor structural damage [24].

In 1976, the [Armed Forces Retirement Home](/Armed_Forces_Retirement_Home) made a notable relocation, moving its operations from [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia) to Gulfport, establishing itself on the former grounds of the [Gulf Coast Military Academy](/Gulf_Coast_Military_Academy). This facility, tragically, was completely destroyed during [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina) in 2005 but was subsequently rebuilt as a significantly larger and more modern complex, reopening in 2010 [25]. A new county courthouse, a testament to the city's ongoing development, was completed in 1977. The early 1990s marked another significant shift, with Gulfport opening its inaugural two casinos in 1993, ushering in a new era of economic diversification. Later that same year, in December, the city underwent a substantial geographical expansion, annexing a considerable 33 square miles (85 km2) of land to its north. This newly incorporated territory notably included [Turkey Creek](/Turkey_Creek_Community_Historic_District), a community of profound historical significance, having been established by emancipated slaves even before the formal founding of Gulfport itself [26]. The early 21st century saw the completion of the impressive [Dan M. Russell Jr. United States Courthouse](/Dan_M._Russell_Jr._United_States_Courthouse) in 2003, further enhancing the city's civic infrastructure [12].

**Damage to the Marine Life Oceanarium and casinos after Hurricane Katrina**

The morning of August 29, 2005, etched itself into the collective memory of Gulfport, as the city was brutally struck by the formidable eastern eyewall of [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina). This catastrophic event brought sustained wind speeds of at least 100 miles per hour (160 km/h) and a devastating storm surge that reached a minimum of 19 feet (5.8 m) [27] [28]. The sheer scale of destruction was immense: 9,571 homes were either severely damaged or completely obliterated, leaving the city grappling with a staggering $3 million deficit in its wake. In the arduous, years-long recovery process, Gulfport received over $300 million in federal aid, a critical lifeline that was meticulously allocated to repair its shattered infrastructure and rebuild essential public facilities [29]. A poignant symbol of the city's enduring resilience and its commitment to renewal arrived in 2020, on the 15th anniversary of [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina)'s landfall, with the grand opening of the [Mississippi Aquarium](/Mississippi_Aquarium). This new, state-of-the-art facility replaced a beloved dolphin-oriented attraction that had been tragically destroyed by the hurricane, marking a new chapter for Gulfport's cultural and environmental landscape [30] [31].

### Geography

According to the often-dry pronouncements of the [United States Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau), the city of Gulfport occupies a total area of 64.2 square miles (166.4 km2). Of this, a substantial 56.9 square miles (147.4 km2) is composed of land, while the remaining 7.3 square miles (19.0 km2), representing approximately 11.40% of its total footprint, is water. A rather convenient arrangement for a port city, one might observe.

Geologically speaking, the region is characterized by the distinctive [Gulfport Formation](/Gulfport_Formation) within [Harrison County](/Harrison_County,_Mississippi). This formation is typically described as a barrier ridge, composed primarily of white, medium- to fine-grained sand, which, upon closer inspection, often reveals a yellow-orange hue closer to the surface. Its thickness, rather predictably, varies, ranging from a modest 5.0 to a more substantial 9.5 meters. Intriguingly, it is known to overlie the [Biloxi Formation](/Biloxi_Formation), suggesting layers of geological history beneath the surface. This particular formation is unequivocally dated to the late [Pleistocene](/Pleistocene) epoch [32].

The [Gulfport Formation](/Gulfport_Formation) itself is not universally present but is confined to a relatively narrow, discontinuous barrier ridge belt, typically between 1 to 3 kilometers wide, which gracefully borders the mainland shore of the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico). It is quite common to find it overlying the [Prairie Formation](/Prairie_Formation) (alluvium) when moving landward, and the [Biloxi Formation](/Biloxi_Formation) (shelf deposits) when venturing closer to the shore. The formation exhibits a gradual upward transition, progressing from poorly to moderately sorted [shoreface](/Shoreface) sands to the more familiar [foreshore sand](/Intertidal_zone) and, finally, the characteristic dunes that dot the coastline. This geological unit stretches impressively from Gulfport, [Mississippi](/Mississippi), eastward all the way to the mouth of the [Ochlockonee River](/Ochlockonee_River) in [Franklin County, Florida](/Franklin_County,_Florida), a testament to its regional scale. It was, rather precisely, deposited during the [Sangamonian](/Sangamonian) interglacial period [32].

