### Climate

Gulfport, with its prime coastal location, is graced, or perhaps burdened, by a quintessential [humid subtropical climate](/Humid_subtropical_climate). This climate is, perhaps mercifully, strongly moderated by the vast expanse of the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico), preventing the truly unbearable extremes found further inland. Winters here are mercifully brief and generally mild; while cold spells do, on occasion, descend upon the city, they rarely linger long enough to become a genuine nuisance. The sight of snow flurries is a rare, almost mythical, occurrence in Gulfport, with any notable accumulation being a phenomenon that largely bypasses most years. Summers, in stark contrast, are predictably long, oppressively hot, and relentlessly humid. Yet, the city's fortunate proximity to the Gulf acts as a natural thermostat, tempering the most extreme summer highs that plague its landlocked counterparts. However, this coastal advantage comes with a significant caveat: Gulfport is acutely susceptible to extreme weather events, most notably the menacing specter of [tropical storm](/Tropical_storm) activity that churns through the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) with alarming regularity. The all-time record high for the city, a rather sweltering 107 °F (41.7 °C), was grimly set on August 26, 2023, proving that even the Gulf's moderating influence has its limits. Conversely, the record coldest temperature, a frigid 1 °F (−17.2 °C), was recorded on February 12, 1899, a stark reminder of historical anomalies. Climate records for the city, for those who truly care about such things, inconveniently date back to 1893; however, until 1998, these records were rather inelegantly stitched together with those of its neighboring city, Biloxi, a testament to the complexities of historical data collection.

