As of the [2020 United States census](/2020_United_States_census), Gulfport was home to 72,926 individuals [38], distributed across 25,559 households, with 15,584 of these constituting families residing within the city limits. This represents a slight resurgence from the 2010 population of 67,793, following a dip from the 2000 census figure of 71,127. The city, of course, is an integral part of the larger [Gulfport–Biloxi metropolitan area](/Gulfport%E2%80%93Biloxi_metropolitan_area), a sprawling urban conglomerate that, according to 2021 estimates, encompasses a population of 416,259 [3] [38].

A closer inspection of the 2020 racial and ethnic composition reveals a dynamic shift in Gulfport's demographic tapestry. Non-Hispanic white residents now constitute 47.15% of the population, a notable decrease from their predominant share of 60.93% in 2000. Meanwhile, the [African American](/African_Americans) population remains the second-largest group, experiencing a significant increase to 38.79% in 2020 from 33.31% in 2000, underscoring a growing diversity. Other groups, while smaller in number, also contribute to this complex mosaic: 0.4% identify as [American Indian or Alaska Native](/Alaska_Native), 1.57% as [Asian](/Asian_Americans), 0.16% as [Pacific Islander](/Pacific_Islander_Americans), and 0.20% as some other race. The most striking change, perhaps, is the substantial growth in the multiracial population, which now accounts for 4.86% of residents, up from a mere 1.14% in 2000. Concurrently, the [Hispanic or Latino](/Hispanic_and_Latino_Americans) population, encompassing individuals of any race, has also seen considerable expansion, rising to 6.88% in 2020 from 2.11% in 2000. These figures paint a picture of a city becoming increasingly diverse, reflecting broader national trends, whether one finds that fascinating or merely an inevitable statistical outcome.

