#### Tourism

Gulfport's economic narrative is one of persistent, almost stubborn, evolution. From its humble, rather gritty beginnings as a lumber port, a place defined by the scent of pine and hard labor, the city has gracefully, or perhaps opportunistically, diversified its economic portfolio. With approximately 6.7 miles (10.8 kilometers) of pristine, almost blindingly white sand beaches stretching along the shimmering expanse of the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico), Gulfport has undeniably transformed itself into a coveted tourism destination. This transformation is largely attributable to the allure of [Mississippi's coast casinos](/Casino), which, with their promise of fleeting fortune and endless entertainment, draw visitors like moths to a particularly garish flame. Gulfport has cemented its reputation by serving as host to a variety of popular cultural events, each a spectacle in its own right. These include the cheerfully named "World's Largest Fishing Rodeo," the nostalgic parade of classic cars known as "Cruisin' the Coast," the vibrant "Black Spring Break," and the rather aggressively named "Smokin' the Sound" speedboat races. Beyond the glitz and the roar, Gulfport maintains its identity as a thriving residential community, boasting a robust mercantile center that caters to the everyday needs of its inhabitants. The city also offers a charming blend of historic neighborhoods and home sites, alongside diverse shopping opportunities that range from the mundane to the slightly more exotic. For those seeking respite, several motels are conveniently scattered throughout the area, ready to accommodate visitors drawn by the promise of golfing greens, the clatter of casino chips, and the myriad of water-sport tourism options. Among its notable attractions, Gulfport is proudly home to the [Island View Casino](/Island_View_Casino), one of a dozen such establishments that dot the alluring [Mississippi Gulf Coast](/Mississippi_Gulf_Coast), each vying for the attention and disposable income of eager patrons.

### Arts and culture

In Gulfport, one finds a curious blend of the contemporary and the historically resonant, a cultural landscape that refuses to be easily categorized.

#### [Mississippi Aquarium](/Mississippi_Aquarium)

The [Mississippi Aquarium](/Mississippi_Aquarium), a marvel of modern aquatic exhibition, officially opened its doors on August 29, 2020 [43]. This expansive 5.8-acre (2.3 ha) complex is a thoughtfully designed integration of both indoor and outdoor habitats, meticulously crafted to house an impressive collection of more than 200 species of animals and over 50 species of native plants [44]. Its very existence is a testament to the city's resilience, as it proudly stands as a replacement for a beloved, dolphin-oriented facility that was tragically destroyed by the unforgiving wrath of [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina). It's a phoenix, if you will, but with more fish.

#### [Fort Massachusetts](/Fort_Massachusetts_(Mississippi))

Off the coast, on [West Ship Island](/Ship_Island_(Mississippi)), stands [Fort Massachusetts](/Fort_Massachusetts_(Mississippi)), a stoic sentinel of stone. This historic fort was constructed in the aftermath of the [War of 1812](/War_of_1812), a period when national security was, perhaps, taken a bit more seriously. It remained in active use, a silent guardian against perceived threats, until 1903. Today, stripped of its martial purpose, it endures as a captivating historical tourist attraction, nestled peacefully within the serene expanse of the [Gulf Islands National Seashore](/Gulf_Islands_National_Seashore).

#### [Turkey Creek Community Historic District](/Turkey_Creek_Community_Historic_District)

The [Turkey Creek Community Historic District](/Turkey_Creek_Community_Historic_District) represents a profound and often overlooked chapter in American history. This settlement was established by courageous, newly emancipated [African Americans](/African_Americans) during the challenging [Reconstruction Era](/Reconstruction_Era) that followed the tumultuous [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War) [45]. Its continued existence and recognition serve as a vital reminder of the enduring spirit and foundational contributions of these communities, predating and in many ways shaping the very city of Gulfport.

### Government

Main article: [List of mayors of Gulfport, Mississippi](/List_of_mayors_of_Gulfport,_Mississippi)

Gulfport operates under a [strong mayor-council](/Mayor%E2%80%93council_government) form of government, a structure that, in theory, provides clear executive leadership. The city is pragmatically subdivided into seven distinct wards, each represented by members who are elected to the Gulfport City Council, ensuring a degree of local representation [46] [47]. The current occupant of the mayoral office, Hugh Keating, is presently serving his inaugural term, navigating the complexities of municipal governance [48].

The Gulfport Police Department maintains a considerable force, comprising 160 sworn personnel who uphold the law and an additional 80 civilian staff who keep the administrative gears turning. Its operations are bolstered by the invaluable assistance of the U.S. Coast Guard, which, with a rather impressive fleet of 9 boats operating out of the [Port of Gulfport](/Port_of_Gulfport)—4 of which are dedicated Patrol Boats—actively monitors the waters. The Gulfport Coast Guard station itself is staffed by 110 dedicated members, a mix of Active, Reserve, and Coast Guard Auxiliary personnel, who, with an almost alarming regularity, respond to an average of 300 search and rescue cases annually. One can only imagine the stories they could tell.

The Gulfport Fire Department, a venerable institution established in 1908, stands ready to provide a comprehensive suite of emergency services. Its professional firefighters are tasked with fire suppression, critical HAZMAT response, and specialized technical rescue services, all diligently performed within the municipal boundaries of Gulfport, [Mississippi](/Mississippi) [49]. The GFD operates out of 11 active stations, strategically positioned to ensure rapid response times. For EMS-related emergencies, the GFD works in seamless conjunction with [American Medical Response](/American_Medical_Response), ensuring a coordinated and efficient response to medical crises.

### Education

#### Upstairs in Gulfport Public Library

The educational landscape of the [City](/City) of Gulfport is served by a dual system: the [Gulfport School District](/Gulfport_School_District), which caters to its immediate urban population, and the [Harrison County School District](/Harrison_County_School_District), which extends its reach to the broader county area. For those pursuing higher education, the [Harrison County](/Harrison_County,_Mississippi) Campus of [Mississippi Gulf Coast Community College](/Mississippi_Gulf_Coast_Community_College) is conveniently located within Gulfport, offering a vital pathway to associate degrees and vocational training [50].

Prior to the devastating impact of [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina), [William Carey University](/William_Carey_University) maintained a satellite campus in Gulfport, a testament to its commitment to providing accessible higher education. However, the hurricane's destructive force necessitated a significant relocation. In 2009, the university inaugurated its new, purpose-built [Tradition Campus](/Tradition_Campus), strategically constructed off [Mississippi Highway 67](/Mississippi_Highway_67) in the northern reaches of [Harrison County](/Harrison_County,_Mississippi), a move that underscored resilience and adaptation [51].

Further west, in the adjacent city of [Long Beach](/Long_Beach,_Mississippi), lies the Gulf Park Campus of the [University of Southern Mississippi](/University_of_Southern_Mississippi). This campus, unfortunately, bore the brunt of extensive damage during [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina) in 2005. As late as 2012, repairs and renovations to its various campus buildings were still very much in progress, a tangible reminder of the long-term recovery efforts required after such a catastrophic event [52].

### Media

*   See also: [List of newspapers in Mississippi](/List_of_newspapers_in_Mississippi), [List of radio stations in Mississippi](/List_of_radio_stations_in_Mississippi), and [List of television stations in Mississippi](/List_of_television_stations_in_Mississippi)

Headquartered directly in Gulfport [53], [The Sun Herald](/The_Sun_Herald) serves as the indispensable local [newspaper](/Newspaper) for Gulfport, Biloxi, and the myriad of other cities scattered across the [Mississippi Gulf Coast](/Mississippi_Gulf_Coast) [54]. This publication gained national recognition, and perhaps a touch of weary pride, when it was awarded the prestigious 2006 [Pulitzer Prize](/Pulitzer_Prize) in journalism for its unflinching and comprehensive coverage of [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina) [55].

The airwaves of Gulfport are a busy place, hosting six distinct [FM](/FM_broadcasting) radio stations. These include W209CF at 89.7, WA0Y at 91.7 (an affiliate of [American Family Radio](/American_Family_Radio)), [WGBL](/WGBL) at 96.7, [WGCM-FM](/WGCM-FM) at 102.3, WAIP-LP at 103.9, and [WLGF](/WLGF) at 107.1 (broadcasting the sounds of [K-Love](/K-Love)) [56]. Not to be outdone, three [AM](/AM_broadcasting) radio stations also call Gulfport home, each extending its reach with convenient FM translators: [WQFX](/WQFX_(AM)) at 1130 (via W254DJ at 98.7), [WGCM](/WGCM_(AM)) at 1240 (via W265DH at 100.9), and [WROA](/WROA) at 1390 (via W261CU at 100.1) [57].

For those who prefer their news and entertainment delivered visually, Gulfport is served by a robust selection of television stations. These include the [ABC](/American_Broadcasting_Company) affiliate [WLOX](/WLOX) and its [CBS](/CBS) affiliate counterpart, [WLOX-DT2](/WLOX-DT2) [58]. Additionally, the [Fox Broadcasting Company](/Fox_Broadcasting_Company) affiliate [WXXV](/WXXV) broadcasts on 25.1, accompanied by its subchannels offering [NBC](/NBC) programming on 25.2, [CW+](/CW%2B) content on 25.3, and the offerings of [Defy TV](/Defy_TV) on 25.4 [59]. It is worth noting that [WLOX](/WLOX) also garnered the distinguished [Peabody Award](/Peabody_Award) for its exceptional coverage of [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina), further cementing the region's media outlets as pillars of information during crisis [60].

Beyond news and daily programming, Gulfport has also served as a backdrop for various cinematic and television productions. These include the 2016 action film [Precious Cargo](/Precious_Cargo_(film)) [61], the festive 2017 TV movie *Christmas in Mississippi* [62], and the 2015 television series [The Astronaut Wives Club](/The_Astronaut_Wives_Club) [63], among other productions that have found inspiration in the city's unique charm.

### Transportation

**[Coast Transit Authority](/Coast_Transit_Authority) buses at the transit center in Gulfport**

For those wishing to arrive or depart by air, Gulfport/Biloxi and the wider [Mississippi Gulf Coast](/Mississippi_Gulf_Coast) area are served by the [Gulfport–Biloxi International Airport](/Gulfport%E2%80%93Biloxi_International_Airport), providing vital commercial air service to the region.

Within the region itself, the [Coast Transit Authority](/Coast_Transit_Authority) endeavors to provide public transportation, offering both fixed-route bus services and specialized paratransit options for those who require them. It's a system that gets people where they need to go, albeit sometimes at a pace that suggests the universe has all the time in the world.

Major roads and highways dissect and connect Gulfport with the wider world. [Interstate 10](/Interstate_10_in_Mississippi), a crucial east–west artery, bisects the middle section of Gulfport, facilitating rapid transit. [U.S. 90](/U.S._90), a scenic route that hugs the coastline in this region, also runs east–west, specifically through the bustling downtown area. From the north, [U.S. 49](/U.S._49) makes its definitive terminus in Gulfport, funneling traffic directly into the city.

Until the devastating arrival of [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina) in 2005, [Amtrak](/Amtrak)'s venerable [Sunset Limited](/Sunset_Limited) passenger train, which traditionally offered service from Los Angeles all the way to Orlando, made regular stops at [Gulfport station](/Gulfport_station) [64] [65]. This connection was a lifeline for many, but the hurricane's destruction severed it. Looking further back into history, well into the 1960s, the [Louisville and Nashville](/Louisville_and_Nashville_Railroad) railway company operated several daily trains, each making convenient stops in Gulfport. These included storied services such as the [Crescent](/Crescent_(train)), the [Gulf Wind](/Gulf_Wind), the [Humming Bird](/Humming_Bird_(train)), the [Pan-American](/Pan-American_(train)), and the [Piedmont Limited](/Piedmont_Limited), offering varied destinations that spanned [New Orleans](/New_Orleans), [Cincinnati](/Cincinnati), [Atlanta](/Atlanta), [New York City](/New_York_City), and [Jacksonville](/Jacksonville) [66]. In a testament to perseverance, or perhaps just stubborn bureaucratic will, Amtrak service is slated to make a return on August 18, 2025, with the establishment of the new [Mardi Gras Service](/Mardi_Gras_Service), which will once again connect Gulfport to key cities along the [Gulf Coast](/Gulf_Coast_of_the_United_States) via the revived [Gulfport Station](/Gulfport_station) [67].

